	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yeah, the up-right diagonal is only suited to pressing buttons individually. Interestingly, the design of the SNES controller is a hybrid, though functionality-wise it's clear the up-left diagonal won out. The controller's two pairs of buttons are each arranged in an up-right diagonal, but the hardware mapping is in an up-left diagonal. That is, when you read the controller NES-style, you get Y and B rather than B and A, because those are the equivalent as far as the thumb is concerned.

		

